Apple today has released iOS 13.3 and iPadOS 13.3 to the public.

For the iPhone and iPad, iOS 13.3 and iPadOS 13.3 include support for Communication Limits in Screen Time. This allows you to set specific limitations on who and when you can communicate with. During allotted screen time, you can allow communication with everyone, but during downtime you could limit communication to certain people.

This feature is especially useful for parents. For example, parents can block their kids from communication with everyone except themselves after a certain time of day. Screen Time Communication Limits apply to the Phone app, Messages app, and FaceTime.

Another change in iOS 13.3 is a new setting that allows you to disable the Memoji and Animoji stickers from always appearing on the emoji keyboard. With iOS 13, Apple increased the prominence of its Memoji stickers by placing them directly alongside regular emojis. Following complaints from many users about this change, Apple has added this new setting with iOS 13.3. This option can be found in Settings > General > Keyboard > Emoji.

iOS 13.3 also has new security features. The Safari browser also supports FIDO2 security keys over Lightning, USB or NFC.

iOS 12.4.4 has also been released for older iPhones with security and performance improvements. It is available for iPhone 5S, iPhone 6, iPad Air, iPad Mini 2/3, and iPod touch 6th-gen.

Other changes in iOS 13.3 include a variety of bug fixes and performance improvements, updates to Apple News, wireless charging improvements, and more.

Based on checks within Apple's supply chain, Susquehanna analyst Mehdi Hosseini expects 5G-enabled iPhones to launch in two phases, including sub-6GHz models in September 2020 and mmWave models in December 2020 or January 2021.

The allegedly delayed launch of mmWave models stems from Apple's decision to use its own antenna-in-package modules instead of relying on a third-party supplier, said Hosseini, according to StreetInsider.

mmWave is the fastest 5G, utilizing new spectrum to provide theoretical download speeds of over 1 Gbps. Sub-6GHz is slower than mmWave, but it is still faster than 4G LTE and has broader coverage that makes it more suitable for rural areas.

caption:
Do you start your day with a glass of milk?

Let's take a second to pay respects to Dr. Verghese Kurien, a humble revolutionary who pioneered 'White Revolution in India' with efforts to uplift the milk production sector. On National Milk Day, chefs from Raviz Ashtamudi visited our own organic farm in Kollam. The farm has Gir, Kankrej, Kasargod Kullan and Vechur cows which are considered to be the best cow breeds. Raviz Ashtamudi also offers A2 milk which is produced from the Gir Cows that are grazed in our own farm, bringing the goodness of milk in it's best natural state where no machines are used and are fed organic fodder. A2 milk also has high nutritional value, it helps in cleaning the cholesterol deposits, prevents lifestyle diseases, immunological disorders and increases immunity power.

It‚Äôs a great place to get off Kerala‚Äôs beaten tourist path for a couple of days if you want something a bit different.
Located 80 kilometres from Thiruvananthapuram, Kollam is famous for its beach, temples, backwaters and fishing harbours. This is one of the oldest port in the Arabian Sea.

caption:
Calicut Tuk Tuk Tour by Tyndis ! 
Among the Tuk- Tuk drivers in Kerala, Calicut auto drivers are considered as most reliable and sincere ones. 
If you are a tourist staying in one of the homestays or resorts in Calicut or if you are in a transit break, a Tuk Tuk tour around Calicut is a must-do. To deep dive into the rich culture and heritage of this town, one needs to take Calicut Tuk Tuk Tour with¬†Tyndis.

Tuk-Tuks (locally known as Auto Rickshaws) are a great way of seeing any town or city in India. Most of the ancient landmarks that interests tourists are tucked in narrow alleys, which are best explored, in a private tuk-tuk tour. 
Mr.Sajeev, Tyndis Tuk Tyk driver is from Calicut itself who know the roads well. He takes you to the hidden gems through the shortest route and do a great job in telling stories associated with the places you visit.¬†¬†Tuk Tuk Tour in Calicut is made special with the amazing care and personalized service ensured by our drivers.

Read our blog for more details :- https://www.tyndisheritage.com/benefits-of-tuk-tuk-tour-in-kerala

Among the Tuk- Tuk drivers in Kerala, Calicut auto drivers are considered as most reliable and sincere ones. 
If you are a tourist staying in one of the homestays or resorts in Calicut or if you are in a transit break, a Tuk Tuk tour around Calicut is a must-do. To deep dive into the rich culture and heritage of this town, one needs to take Calicut Tuk Tuk Tour with¬†Tyndis.

Mr.Sajeev and team, Well trained Tyndis Tuk Tyk drivers are from Calicut itself who know the roads well. They take you to the hidden gems through the shortest route and do a great job in telling stories associated with the places you visit.¬†¬†Tuk Tuk Tour in Calicut is made special with the amazing care and personalized service ensured by our drivers.

Tyndis UK group is enjoying Calicut Tuk Tuk tour :) PC - Binusha , Tyndis Story Teller.

caption:
A privilege and an honour to have legendary Chef Damu (as he is fondly called) dine with us at The Raviz Kadavu. He was in all praise of the Chefs at the Raviz Kadavu and the gourmet offerings - specially the Malabari Biriyani and the Aleppey Fish Curry with raw mango.

Chef K. Damodharan, also known as Chef Damu,is an Indian chef best known for winning the Guinness World Record for the longest cooking marathon by a single individual in 2010.He has hosted cookery shows for various television channels and became the first Indian chef to receive PhD in Hotel Management and Catering Technology.

In December of 2010, Damodharan cooked 617 dishes comprising of 190 kilograms of food in a day. He began cooking at 8 o'clock in the morning on December 21 and cooked for a period of 24 hours, 30 minutes, and 12 seconds. Damodharan was also a judge at The Hindu's Our State Our Taste competition for 15 cities in Tamil Nadu.

#StoriesofMalabar by Tyndis Heritage

The #Stories of #GunnyStreet in Calicut! 
Episode #1 releasing on YouTube tomorrow (13/03/2020) at 05:00 P.M. IST! 
#Watch it here www.youtube.com/channel/UCZeZxzqgPj-0m3lzZPk0jQQ

Big markets always have an inseparable relationship with gunny bags. This Tyndis Storytelling Tour in Calicut through Gunny Street has fascinating stories about the life cycle of the thousands of Gunny sacks that daily arrived in Calicut! Get a glimpse of the Coir Godowns of Calicut as well! 
Click to watch the #Trailer of #StoriesofMalabar
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wEvjFMGXaaw&t=6s

Stories of #Malabar is the first segment of Tyndis Media's series about the untold stories of #NorthKerala. This series of Stories of Malabar comprises of sixteen interesting stories about #Calicut and its rich flavours.  #keralatourism #calicutstories #kozhikode #keralam #calicuttourismcalicutbeach #calicutdiaries #calicutfood #calicutvibes #kozhikode #kozhikoden #kozhikodenspecial #raviz #keralatourism #kerala #keralagram

caption:
The Taj Mahal is located on the right bank of the Yamuna River in a vast Mughal garden that encompasses nearly 17 hectares, in the Agra District in Uttar Pradesh. It was built by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his wife Mumtaz Mahal with construction¬†of the mosque, the guest house and the main gateway on the south, the outer courtyard and its cloisters.
The Taj Mahal is considered to be the greatest architectural achievement in the whole range of Indo-Islamic architecture. Its recognised architectonic beauty has a rhythmic combination of solids and voids, concave and convex and light shadow;

The¬†Bibi Ka Maqbara¬† in¬†#aurangabad It bears a striking resemblance to the¬†#tajmahal 
My Aurangabad trip was truly amazing along with festivities of a family wedding the visit to the Bibi ka Maqbara was the icing on the cake .

The¬†Bibi Ka Maqbara¬† was commissioned in 1660 by the¬†Mughal emperor¬†Aurangzeb¬†in the memory of his first and chief wife¬†Dilras Banu Begum¬†(posthumously known as Rabia-ud-Daurani) and is considered to be a symbol of Aurangzeb's 'conjugal fidelity'.¬†It bears a striking resemblance to the¬†Taj Mahal, the mausoleum of Aurangzeb's mother,¬†Mumtaz Mahal.  #maharashtra  #india  #love #ig #instagram  #photography  #instagood

caption:
SELAMAT HARI RAYA NYEPI üôè
.
üá®üáµ Nyepi est le jour du silence qui se d√©roule chaque ann√©e √† Bali. Cette magnifique √Æle est alors mise au repos au m√™me titre que ses habitants. Pas de travail, pas d'activit√©s, pas de lumi√®re, pas d'√©lectricit√©, pas d'internet, personne dans les rues, a√©roport et magasins ferm√©s... Seul les lieux de soins sont ouverts. Les balinais restent alors chez eux, en famille et profitent de ce temps pour avoir une r√©flexion int√©rieure sur leur vie. Pour les plus strictes, pas de parole. Les balinais pensent alors que les mauvais esprits se baladant dans les rues et ne trouvant personne, vont alors s'en aller et donc ne pas perturber pas la vie de l'√Æle.
Nous nous r√©jouissions √† l'avance et depuis plus d'un an de vivre cette f√™te au sein m√™me de Bali mais cette p√©riode de rapatriement et confinement en a d√©cid√© autrement. Ce ne sera que pour mieux le faire une autre fois...
.
üá¨üáß Nyepi is the day of silence that takes place every year in Bali. This magnificent island is then put to rest just like its inhabitants. No work, no activities, no light, no electricity, no internet, no one in the streets, closed airport and shops... Only the places of care are open. The Balinese stay at home, with family and take advantage of this time to have an inner reflection on their life.  For the strictest, no word. The Balinese think that the evil spirits wandering in the streets and finding no one, will then go away and therefore not disturb the life of the island.
We were looking forward to this celebration for over a year, but this period of repatriation and confinement has decided otherwise.
That's for do it better another time...
.

caption:
THE ONE THING YOU'LL NEVER GET BACK

You already know that time is the only thing we can not buy or buy back

Second by second, minute by minute, this value we place on said measured thing that is time is consistently fleeting, mysteriously exhausting within itself all that hath been said and that hath that been done

And all too often we humans are so busy planning our future or worrying about it. Or the inverse, we're reliving our past, at best, or more likely reliving our past mistakes and regrets

But what about the present moment

What about now

Many of us spend so much time stuck in the past and/or future that we never really live in the present moment at all

And this is just ludicrous for we're stuck living in something that doesn't exist, over and over and over again

You see the past doesn't exist and neither does the future. When you were actually experiencing those memories from the past, it was now. And when the future that you're planning for or worried about arrives, it wil be now

All we ever really have is now

This very moment that is upon us

This very moment that we're in

THIS PRESENT MOMENT

And mentally living anywhere outside of the present moment leads to all sorts of ailments that, like always, start in the psyche

It is well known and documented in the field of psychology that depression stems from living in the past and anxiety stems from worry of the future. And both of these are out of our control

Yet the one thing we can control, change and manipulate for the better is our present moment

So the next time you find yourself worrying or sullen may I offer these steps:

Stop whatever your doing

Take 3 long deep breaths

Ask yourself if you are ok right now, in this very moment, (not later, not before)

If not, ask yourself what you need to be ok right now

Remind yourself that you have health, water, shelter, love to give and someone who loves you

Now ask yourself again in this very moment, what more do you need to be ok

And if there's something you truly need, write it down and then write down all the solutions you can come up with to get what you need. Then write down the steps to get there

Inspired by "The Power Of Now"

caption:
#SindyLutz. Untitled (Seascape), 2008. Mixed media. 8‚Äù x 8‚Äù.
Sindy Lutz (b. 1966) grew up at the Jersey Shore. Her seascapes reflect the impact of staring at the ocean and bay in all it‚Äôs changing moods, light and color over many years. These small drawings‚Äîmade of graphite and crayon‚Äîare drawn spontaneously from deep memories of living near the sea. They started as an escape from previous figurative work that sprang from frustration and early childhood trauma. For Lutz, these drawings are the joy of a fresh breath of sea atmosphere and sunlight. A safe place for the imagination to rest and wander.
‚ÄúThe sea is a mirror
We feel our own anger in it‚Äôs thrashing waves
Our hope in it‚Äôs smoldering sunrises
Our fear in it‚Äôs dark moonless nights‚Äù

caption:
sorry for the poor picture quality, this was taken 6 years ago but I adore this picture and memory to go along with it. 
I don‚Äôt like to disclose my fears on social media but i have to let you know that I‚Äôm fucking terrified of bridges-not heights or the water below, just bridges. I don‚Äôt know why but I kind of attribute it back to with the 35W bridge collapsed years ago and that bridge is VERY familiar to me and drive across it often (while having minor panic attacks). Anyways, 6 years ago in New Zealand in the South Island I had to opportunity to bungee jump and decided I did NOT want to do it. After watching people I was traveling with sign up, I on a whim handed my credit card over and decided to bungee with @ajhackettbungynz 
I ended up diving off (I‚Äôll post a video later) and it was such a liberating, freeing experience. And honestly, really helped with my fear of bridges haha! I‚Äôm sooooo happy I bought that ticket on a whim and desperately want to bungee again soon! 
Love you, New Zealand üòò
